article.description:
Coretta Brown scored 19 points and hit
a free throw with 4.3 seconds left as No. 8 North Carolina beat
Clemson 70-66 Sunday.
article.headline: Floyd scores season-high 27 points in loss
article.linkText: Brown, North Carolina edge upset-minded Clemson
article.story:
CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- Nikita Bell gave  (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 8 AP) North Carolina the second-half boost it desperately needed Sunday.
	   
With Clemson holding a three-point lead at the 14:39 mark, Bell
outscored the Tigers 8-1 over the next 2:09 to put the Tar Heels
ahead to stay en route to a 70-66 win.

	   "When she gets going like that, she can really get on a roll,''
North Carolina coach Sylvia Hatchell said.

	   Coretta Brown scored 19 points and hit a free throw with 4.3
seconds left to seal it for North Carolina (23-2, 12-1 Atlantic
Coast Conference), which won its eighth straight league game and
fourth in a row against the Tigers (12-11, 4-8).

	   Candace Sutton added a season-high 18 points and Nikita Bell had
15 points and eight steals for the Tar Heels.

	   The Tigers stayed close by dominating the boards, outrebounding
North Carolina 48-35 behind Tia Andrew's 12 rebounds. Clemson finished with 20 offensive boards.

	   It was just the third time the Tar Heels were outrebounded this
season.

	   "We're happy to win, but not with our performance, especially
the rebounding,'' Hatchell said. "They dominated the rebounding
and that's why the game was so close.''

	   The winter storm that blanketed the Mid-Atlantic region dumped
sleet and freezing rain in much of North Carolina, and the game had
an announced attendance of 331 in the 10,180-seat Carmichael
Auditorium.

	   U.S. Sen. Elizabeth Dole, who replaced longtime North Carolina
conservative Jesse Helms, was to serve as honorary coach, but she
was unable to attend.

	   Chrissy Floyd scored a season-high 27 points on 11-for-20
shooting for Clemson, which has lost seven of nine. Julie Aderhold
added 12.

	   "We have to take some pressure off Chrissy,'' Clemson coach Jim
Davis said. "Chrissy is a heck of a player, but she's been under
pressure all season long -- doubled and chased by everybody.''

	   Clemson led 54-51 on a layup by Lakeia Stokes early in the
second half, but Bell answered with eight straight points. She
capped the run with two free throws for a 59-55 lead with 11:37
left.

	   "One player doesn't get it done,'' Bell said.

	   The Tar Heels pushed to a 66-58 lead with 8:30 to play and held
the Tigers without a field goal for the next 10{ minutes.

	   Still, Clemson rallied late, scoring eight unanswered points to
pull within three. The Tigers had three chances to tie it in the
final 80 seconds, but couldn't overtake the Tar Heels.

	   Leah Metcalf rebounded Floyd's last miss and passed to Brown,
who hit the final free throw with 4.3 seconds left.

	   Both teams shot 50 percent in the first half and went into
halftime tied at 42.
